Bro… here’s my suspicion now:
You are using:

    Gazebo Sim (gz-sim / Harmonic)

    Plugin: gz-sim-mecanum-drive-system

This plugin is already designed to simulate mecanum kinematics.

That means manually forcing anisotropic friction with fdir1 may actually fight the plugin.

So we may have overcomplicated it.
New diagnosis (much stronger)

I now think the issue is one of these two:
1) Wheel collision shape is wrong for mecanum

You use:

<cylinder radius="${wheel_radius}" length="${wheel_width}"/>

A plain cylinder behaves like a normal wheel.

Even with friction hacks, pure strafe can still fail.
2) Your wheel collision is offset in Y

You still have:

Right wheels:

c_y = 0.008

Left wheels:

c_y = -0.008

That means collision cylinder center is shifted by 8 mm.

For mecanum, even small offsets matter a lot.

During pure strafe:

    wheel torques should cancel rotation exactly

    if one wheel contact point is offset → creates moment

    robot rotates instead of strafing

And your symptom is EXACTLY that:

    tries to strafe → rotates 90°

My recommendation: STOP changing 10 things at once

Let’s do one clean test.
TEST A (important)

Set ALL wheels to simple isotropic friction:

<mu>1</mu>
<mu2>1</mu2>

And remove fdir1 completely:

Delete:

<fdir1>...</fdir1>

TEST B

Set ALL wheel collisions centered:

Change:

c_y="0.008"
c_y="-0.008"

to:

c_y="0"

for all 4 wheels.

Yes — all zero.
TEST C

Keep plugin original:

FL = left_f
FR = right_f
BL = left_b
BR = right_b

(which you already have)

Bro, after 40+ messages debugging, my gut says:
The root problem is not plugin math.

It’s wheel collision contact points not symmetric.

One question — and this may settle everything:
When you select collision wireframe in Gazebo, does each cylinder pass exactly through wheel center?

Just:

    YES
    or

    NO

No guessing 😄 just what you see visually.

